  "timeframe": "1D",
  "market_context": "On GC1!, Friday of the prior week prints a candle two closure into a daily point of interest (OB/FVG around 4500–4540). On BLL (CL1!), a similar setup forms near 49.79 with the RB11 trendline, providing a correlated context for daily bias analysis.",
  "key_observation": "A Friday candle two closure at a point of interest legitimizes trading Monday as candle three. Additionally, an intraweek reversal does not require a candle two at a POI when an SMT divergence between correlated assets (BLL vs RB11) is present.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On GC1! daily, identify Friday's candle two closure into the OB/FVG point of interest around 4500–4540.",
    "Step 2: Treat Monday as candle three and look for continuation higher off Friday's reversal.",
    "Step 3: Monday expands away, signalling that the weekly candle wants to go higher, so look to trade candle four continuation.",
    "Step 4: After the small candle four continuation, wait for a new phase of price; observe another candle two closure setup.",
    "Step 5: On BLL, the next day takes out previous day low and closes back above, with an SMT divergence versus RB11 — this validates the swing/candle two even without a clean POI.",
    "Step 6: With Monday expanding away from the SMT swing, treat Tuesday–Wednesday as consolidation, Thursday as a candle two reversal, then look for Friday continuation and another Monday candle four continuation."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "Mondays are tradable when Friday provides a candle two reversal at a POI, making Monday candle three. An intraweek reversal can also be confirmed by SMT divergence between correlated assets instead of requiring a candle two at a POI.",
